  <graph edgedefault="directed">
    <node id="VENTILATION SYSTEM DESIGN">
      <data key="d0">VENTILATION SYSTEM DESIGN</data>
      <data key="d1">ENGINEERING_CONTROL</data>
      <data key="d2">An engineering control involving the design and optimization of a mechanically ventilated room system to reduce airborne infectious disease transmission risk. In the text, it is the main intervention, emphasizing airflow organization and contaminant movement from source to exhaust rather than simply increasing total airflow.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.98</data>
      <data key="d4">3fc1e87d-c54a-447e-9229-2850cf6a1b9b_chunk_2,3fc1e87d-c54a-447e-9229-2850cf6a1b9b_chunk_3</data>
      <data key="d5">3fc1e87d-c54a-447e-9229-2850cf6a1b9b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SOURCE-TO-EXHAUST PATH CONTROL STRATEGY">
      <data key="d0">SOURCE-TO-EXHAUST PATH CONTROL STRATEGY</data>
      <data key="d1">ENGINEERING_CONTROL</data>
      <data key="d2">A proposed engineering control strategy that improves contaminant control by maintaining an effective, uninterrupted path between the contaminant source and the exhaust. The text presents this as a key mechanism for reducing airborne infectious disease exposure in an isolation room.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">3fc1e87d-c54a-447e-9229-2850cf6a1b9b_chunk_2</data>
      <data key="d5">3fc1e87d-c54a-447e-9229-2850cf6a1b9b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="VENTILATION AIRFLOW RATE">
      <data key="d0">VENTILATION AIRFLOW RATE</data>
      <data key="d1">DOSE_OR_RATE</data>
      <data key="d2">The ventilation flow rate supplied or exhausted by the room ventilation system. The text notes that increasing this rate can improve dilution under constant source conditions, but may not by itself improve ventilation effectiveness or infection control.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">3fc1e87d-c54a-447e-9229-2850cf6a1b9b_chunk_2</data>
      <data key="d5">3fc1e87d-c54a-447e-9229-2850cf6a1b9b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="AIR CHANGES PER HOUR (ACH)">
      <data key="d0">AIR CHANGES PER HOUR (ACH)</data>
      <data key="d1">EFFECTIVENESS_MEASURE</data>
      <data key="d2">Measured ventilation performance metric used to quantify air exchange in the bus under different operating and window-opening conditions.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.98</data>
      <data key="d4">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee_chunk_3</data>
      <data key="d5">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee</data>
    </node>
    <node id="AIRBORNE INFECTIOUS DISEASE AGENTS">
      <data key="d0">AIRBORNE INFECTIOUS DISEASE AGENTS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Airborne infectious agents whose transport and exposure are the focus of the ventilation analysis. These are the hazards the ventilation design and control strategy aim to contain or remove.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.89</data>
      <data key="d4">3fc1e87d-c54a-447e-9229-2850cf6a1b9b_chunk_2</data>
      <data key="d5">3fc1e87d-c54a-447e-9229-2850cf6a1b9b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="INFECTION RISK TO OCCUPANTS">
      <data key="d0">INFECTION RISK TO OCCUPANTS</data>
      <data key="d1">EFFECTIVENESS_MEASURE</data>
      <data key="d2">The likelihood that room occupants acquire infection from airborne infectious agents. The text uses reduction of this risk as the main intended outcome of optimized ventilation design.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.93</data>
      <data key="d4">3fc1e87d-c54a-447e-9229-2850cf6a1b9b_chunk_2</data>
      <data key="d5">3fc1e87d-c54a-447e-9229-2850cf6a1b9b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CONTAMINANT CONCENTRATION">
      <data key="d0">CONTAMINANT CONCENTRATION</data>
      <data key="d1">EFFECTIVENESS_MEASURE</data>
      <data key="d2">The level of airborne contaminant present in the room air. The text states that higher ventilation airflow can dilute contaminant concentration better when the source is constant, although this does not necessarily mean better ventilation effectiveness.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.76</data>
      <data key="d4">3fc1e87d-c54a-447e-9229-2850cf6a1b9b_chunk_2</data>
      <data key="d5">3fc1e87d-c54a-447e-9229-2850cf6a1b9b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="VENTILATION EFFECTIVENESS">
      <data key="d0">VENTILATION EFFECTIVENESS</data>
      <data key="d1">EFFECTIVENESS_MEASURE</data>
      <data key="d2">A measure of how effectively the ventilation system controls contaminant transport and removal relative to exposure risk. The text explicitly distinguishes ventilation effectiveness from simple dilution achieved by increasing airflow rate or ACH.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.87</data>
      <data key="d4">3fc1e87d-c54a-447e-9229-2850cf6a1b9b_chunk_2</data>
      <data key="d5">3fc1e87d-c54a-447e-9229-2850cf6a1b9b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ISOLATION ROOM">
      <data key="d0">ISOLATION ROOM</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">A hospital room intended to isolate potentially infectious patients and control transmission. It is the specific room type used in the paper's hypothetical ventilation design and CFD-based analysis.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.96</data>
      <data key="d4">3fc1e87d-c54a-447e-9229-2850cf6a1b9b_chunk_2</data>
      <data key="d5">3fc1e87d-c54a-447e-9229-2850cf6a1b9b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ENCLOSED AND MECHANICALLY VENTILATED ROOM">
      <data key="d0">ENCLOSED AND MECHANICALLY VENTILATED ROOM</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">A broader room class characterized by enclosure and mechanical ventilation, of which the isolation room is an example in the text. The paper's hypothesis about contaminant path control is stated for this type of room environment.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.78</data>
      <data key="d4">3fc1e87d-c54a-447e-9229-2850cf6a1b9b_chunk_2</data>
      <data key="d5">3fc1e87d-c54a-447e-9229-2850cf6a1b9b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CFD ANALYSIS">
      <data key="d0">CFD ANALYSIS</data>
      <data key="d1">VALIDATION_STUDY</data>
      <data key="d2">A computational fluid dynamics analysis used to examine transport mechanisms, particle paths, and control options for airborne infectious agents. It provides the mechanistic study basis for the paper's proposed ventilation design approach.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">3fc1e87d-c54a-447e-9229-2850cf6a1b9b_chunk_2</data>
      <data key="d5">3fc1e87d-c54a-447e-9229-2850cf6a1b9b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="NOSOCOMIAL INFECTIONS COST IN THE UNITED STATES">
      <data key="d0">NOSOCOMIAL INFECTIONS COST IN THE UNITED STATES</data>
      <data key="d1">COST_PROXY</data>
      <data key="d2">The estimated annual economic burden of nosocomial infections in the United States, reported as $4 billion to $5 billion. In the text, this serves as the financial motivation for improving infection-control design and achieving long-term cost savings.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.75</data>
      <data key="d4">3fc1e87d-c54a-447e-9229-2850cf6a1b9b_chunk_2</data>
      <data key="d5">3fc1e87d-c54a-447e-9229-2850cf6a1b9b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="AIR CHANGE RATE (ACH)">
      <data key="d0">AIR CHANGE RATE (ACH)</data>
      <data key="d1">DOSE_OR_RATE</data>
      <data key="d2">A quantitative ventilation flow-rate parameter representing the number of air changes per hour. The text treats ACH as an important but secondary factor relative to ventilation system design, while noting that higher ACH strengthens the protective effect of increased distance from the patient in transient coughing scenarios. | Measured ventilation performance metric used to quantify air replacement in the route bus. ACH increased with bus speed, was higher with more open windows, depended on which windows were opened, and was much higher with fans set to exhaust than supply.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.96</data>
      <data key="d4">3fc1e87d-c54a-447e-9229-2850cf6a1b9b_chunk_3</data>
      <data key="d5">3fc1e87d-c54a-447e-9229-2850cf6a1b9b,e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee</data>
      <data key="d6">AIR EXCHANGE RATES (ACH)</data>
    </node>
    <node id="INFECTION RISK">
      <data key="d0">INFECTION RISK</data>
      <data key="d1">EFFECTIVENESS_MEASURE</data>
      <data key="d2">The main outcome measure reflecting the likelihood of infection transmission or exposure. In the passage, infection risk is influenced by ventilation system design, airflow path continuity, distance from the patient, and ACH, and generally decreases when exposure conditions are better controlled.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">3fc1e87d-c54a-447e-9229-2850cf6a1b9b_chunk_3</data>
      <data key="d5">3fc1e87d-c54a-447e-9229-2850cf6a1b9b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="PATIENT ROOM">
      <data key="d0">PATIENT ROOM</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">The hospital room environment in which ventilation design and airflow conditions are evaluated for their effects on contaminant transport and infection risk.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.76</data>
      <data key="d4">3fc1e87d-c54a-447e-9229-2850cf6a1b9b_chunk_3</data>
      <data key="d5">3fc1e87d-c54a-447e-9229-2850cf6a1b9b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="THIS STUDY">
      <data key="d0">THIS STUDY</data>
      <data key="d1">VALIDATION_STUDY</data>
      <data key="d2">The study described in the passage that provides evidence on the relative importance of ventilation system design, airflow path continuity, distance from the patient, and ACH for contaminant control and infection risk reduction in patient rooms.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.89</data>
      <data key="d4">3fc1e87d-c54a-447e-9229-2850cf6a1b9b_chunk_3</data>
      <data key="d5">3fc1e87d-c54a-447e-9229-2850cf6a1b9b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="MOST RECENTLY IDENTIFIED ORGANISMS">
      <data key="d0">MOST RECENTLY IDENTIFIED ORGANISMS</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">A nonspecific group of infectious organisms mentioned in the context of future research needs to determine exact transmission modes. They are relevant as potential airborne pathogens whose transmission may be affected by ventilation and airflow conditions.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.4</data>
      <data key="d4">3fc1e87d-c54a-447e-9229-2850cf6a1b9b_chunk_3</data>
      <data key="d5">3fc1e87d-c54a-447e-9229-2850cf6a1b9b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="DISTANCE FROM THE PATIENT">
      <data key="d0">DISTANCE FROM THE PATIENT</data>
      <data key="d1">ENGINEERING_CONTROL</data>
      <data key="d2">A spatial exposure-control factor referring to moving farther away from the patient source. The passage identifies it as a secondary factor that generally reduces infection risk in transient coughing situations, especially under higher flow rates.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.78</data>
      <data key="d4">3fc1e87d-c54a-447e-9229-2850cf6a1b9b_chunk_3</data>
      <data key="d5">3fc1e87d-c54a-447e-9229-2850cf6a1b9b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="NEGATIVE-PRESSURIZED ISOLATION ROOM">
      <data key="d0">NEGATIVE-PRESSURIZED ISOLATION ROOM</data>
      <data key="d1">ENGINEERING_CONTROL</data>
      <data key="d2">A hospital airborne-infection-control intervention that combines negative pressure and controlled ventilation to contain contaminated air within an isolation space and limit its escape to surrounding areas. In the cited 2022 article, it is the primary engineering control whose ventilation performance is evaluated for emergency department use.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.96</data>
      <data key="d4">3fc1e87d-c54a-447e-9229-2850cf6a1b9b_chunk_4</data>
      <data key="d5">3fc1e87d-c54a-447e-9229-2850cf6a1b9b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="VENTILATION">
      <data key="d0">VENTILATION</data>
      <data key="d1">ENGINEERING_CONTROL</data>
      <data key="d2">An engineering control based on air exchange, airflow direction, and contaminant removal to reduce indoor exposure to airborne particles and pathogens. In this text, ventilation is discussed both as a general control strategy and as a design feature of isolation rooms and alternative room configurations. | Ventilation is an engineering control listed as a MeSH/topic term in the text. It refers to air exchange or airflow management used to dilute and remove indoor airborne contaminants such as aerosols. The snippet provides no implementation details, setting, airflow rate, or measured performance.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.95</data>
      <data key="d4">3fc1e87d-c54a-447e-9229-2850cf6a1b9b_chunk_4</data>
      <data key="d5">3fc1e87d-c54a-447e-9229-2850cf6a1b9b,e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee</data>
      <data key="d6">VENTILATION</data>
    </node>
    <node id="DIFFERENT VENTILATION CONFIGURATIONS">
      <data key="d0">DIFFERENT VENTILATION CONFIGURATIONS</data>
      <data key="d1">ENGINEERING_CONTROL</data>
      <data key="d2">Alternative ventilation design or operating arrangements used in hospital isolation rooms. In the cited 2022 study, these configurations are compared for their effects on cough-droplet transport from a COVID-19 patient, making them relevant engineering-control variants.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.78</data>
      <data key="d4">3fc1e87d-c54a-447e-9229-2850cf6a1b9b_chunk_4</data>
      <data key="d5">3fc1e87d-c54a-447e-9229-2850cf6a1b9b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="EMERGENCY DEPARTMENTS">
      <data key="d0">EMERGENCY DEPARTMENTS</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">A hospital care zone for acute evaluation and treatment where rapid patient turnover and undifferentiated respiratory presentations can increase airborne-exposure concerns. In the text, this is the intended deployment setting for the negative-pressurized isolation room.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.85</data>
      <data key="d4">3fc1e87d-c54a-447e-9229-2850cf6a1b9b_chunk_4</data>
      <data key="d5">3fc1e87d-c54a-447e-9229-2850cf6a1b9b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="HOSPITAL ISOLATION ROOM">
      <data key="d0">HOSPITAL ISOLATION ROOM</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">A specialized hospital room used to separate patients and control transmission risk, often through pressure differentials and ventilation management. In the cited literature, it is the setting in which cough-droplet behavior and ventilation configurations are studied.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.83</data>
      <data key="d4">3fc1e87d-c54a-447e-9229-2850cf6a1b9b_chunk_4</data>
      <data key="d5">3fc1e87d-c54a-447e-9229-2850cf6a1b9b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="RESPIRATORY VIRUSES">
      <data key="d0">RESPIRATORY VIRUSES</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">A class of viruses transmitted through respiratory emissions, including aerosols and droplets. The cited review on transmissibility and transmission makes this the most appropriate pathogen-level target for ventilation-related controls in the provided text.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.74</data>
      <data key="d4">3fc1e87d-c54a-447e-9229-2850cf6a1b9b_chunk_4</data>
      <data key="d5">3fc1e87d-c54a-447e-9229-2850cf6a1b9b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="VENTILATION PERFORMANCE EVALUATION OF A NEGATIVE-PRESSURIZED ISOLATION ROOM FOR EMERGENCY DEPARTMENTS">
      <data key="d0">VENTILATION PERFORMANCE EVALUATION OF A NEGATIVE-PRESSURIZED ISOLATION ROOM FOR EMERGENCY DEPARTMENTS</data>
      <data key="d1">VALIDATION_STUDY</data>
      <data key="d2">A 2022 study by Wang F and colleagues that evaluates the ventilation performance of a negative-pressurized isolation room designed for emergency departments. It provides direct evidence on the operation of this engineering control in a healthcare setting.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.94</data>
      <data key="d4">3fc1e87d-c54a-447e-9229-2850cf6a1b9b_chunk_4</data>
      <data key="d5">3fc1e87d-c54a-447e-9229-2850cf6a1b9b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SUMMARY OF HUMAN RESPONSES TO VENTILATION">
      <data key="d0">SUMMARY OF HUMAN RESPONSES TO VENTILATION</data>
      <data key="d1">VALIDATION_STUDY</data>
      <data key="d2">A 2004 review by Seppänen and Fisk summarizing human responses to ventilation. In this extraction, it serves as background evidence supporting the importance of ventilation performance for indoor environmental conditions, though it is not specific to infection-control efficacy.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.57</data>
      <data key="d4">3fc1e87d-c54a-447e-9229-2850cf6a1b9b_chunk_4</data>
      <data key="d5">3fc1e87d-c54a-447e-9229-2850cf6a1b9b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="BEHAVIOR OF COUGH DROPLETS EMITTED FROM COVID-19 PATIENT IN HOSPITAL ISOLATION ROOM WITH DIFFERENT VENTILATION CONFIGURATIONS">
      <data key="d0">BEHAVIOR OF COUGH DROPLETS EMITTED FROM COVID-19 PATIENT IN HOSPITAL ISOLATION ROOM WITH DIFFERENT VENTILATION CONFIGURATIONS</data>
      <data key="d1">VALIDATION_STUDY</data>
      <data key="d2">A 2022 study by Dao and Kim examining how cough droplets from a COVID-19 patient behave in a hospital isolation room under different ventilation configurations. It provides mechanistic evidence linking ventilation design to respiratory particle transport in healthcare spaces.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.91</data>
      <data key="d4">3fc1e87d-c54a-447e-9229-2850cf6a1b9b_chunk_4</data>
      <data key="d5">3fc1e87d-c54a-447e-9229-2850cf6a1b9b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="TRANSMISSIBILITY AND TRANSMISSION OF RESPIRATORY VIRUSES">
      <data key="d0">TRANSMISSIBILITY AND TRANSMISSION OF RESPIRATORY VIRUSES</data>
      <data key="d1">VALIDATION_STUDY</data>
      <data key="d2">A 2021 review by Leung on how respiratory viruses spread and how transmissibility is determined. In this extraction, it provides indirect supporting evidence for why ventilation matters as a control for airborne or aerosol-mediated transmission.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.64</data>
      <data key="d4">3fc1e87d-c54a-447e-9229-2850cf6a1b9b_chunk_4</data>
      <data key="d5">3fc1e87d-c54a-447e-9229-2850cf6a1b9b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="VENTILATION STRATEGIES">
      <data key="d0">VENTILATION STRATEGIES</data>
      <data key="d1">ENGINEERING_CONTROL</data>
      <data key="d2">Engineering control involving ventilation-based airflow management approaches intended to mitigate airborne dispersion in healthcare settings. In the cited 2024 study, these strategies are evaluated for reducing the spread of MERS-CoV within inpatient wards.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.96</data>
      <data key="d4">3fc1e87d-c54a-447e-9229-2850cf6a1b9b_chunk_5</data>
      <data key="d5">3fc1e87d-c54a-447e-9229-2850cf6a1b9b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="MERS-COV">
      <data key="d0">MERS-COV</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Airborne pathogen explicitly identified in the cited study as the infectious agent whose dispersion in air is being mitigated through ventilation strategies in inpatient wards.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.97</data>
      <data key="d4">3fc1e87d-c54a-447e-9229-2850cf6a1b9b_chunk_5</data>
      <data key="d5">3fc1e87d-c54a-447e-9229-2850cf6a1b9b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="INPATIENT WARDS">
      <data key="d0">INPATIENT WARDS</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">Hospital care area serving as the setting for the numerical investigation of airborne dispersion and ventilation-based mitigation of MERS-CoV.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.91</data>
      <data key="d4">3fc1e87d-c54a-447e-9229-2850cf6a1b9b_chunk_5</data>
      <data key="d5">3fc1e87d-c54a-447e-9229-2850cf6a1b9b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="THE AIR WE BREATHE: NUMERICAL INVESTIGATION OF VENTILATION STRATEGIES TO MITIGATE AIRBORNE DISPERSION OF MERS-COV IN INPATIENT WARDS">
      <data key="d0">THE AIR WE BREATHE: NUMERICAL INVESTIGATION OF VENTILATION STRATEGIES TO MITIGATE AIRBORNE DISPERSION OF MERS-COV IN INPATIENT WARDS</data>
      <data key="d1">VALIDATION_STUDY</data>
      <data key="d2">Validation study published in 2024 that uses numerical investigation to assess how ventilation strategies can mitigate airborne dispersion of MERS-CoV in inpatient wards. It provides modeling-based evidence linking the engineering control to the pathogen and hospital setting.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.99</data>
      <data key="d4">3fc1e87d-c54a-447e-9229-2850cf6a1b9b_chunk_5</data>
      <data key="d5">3fc1e87d-c54a-447e-9229-2850cf6a1b9b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="AIRBORNE DISPERSION OF MERS-COV">
      <data key="d0">AIRBORNE DISPERSION OF MERS-COV</data>
      <data key="d1">EFFECTIVENESS_MEASURE</data>
      <data key="d2">Outcome measure representing the extent of airborne spread of MERS-CoV. The cited numerical study evaluates whether ventilation strategies reduce this dispersion in inpatient wards.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.89</data>
      <data key="d4">3fc1e87d-c54a-447e-9229-2850cf6a1b9b_chunk_5</data>
      <data key="d5">3fc1e87d-c54a-447e-9229-2850cf6a1b9b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="WINDOW-OPENING">
      <data key="d0">WINDOW-OPENING</data>
      <data key="d1">ENGINEERING_CONTROL</data>
      <data key="d2">Natural ventilation intervention in the route bus achieved by opening windows. The study reports that ACH increased with bus speed whether windows were open or closed, but ACH was higher when more windows were open, and window placement also mattered. This control was associated with the largest modeled reduction in average infection risk.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.98</data>
      <data key="d4">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee_chunk_2</data>
      <data key="d5">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee</data>
    </node>
    <node id="VENTILATION FANS SET TO EXHAUST">
      <data key="d0">VENTILATION FANS SET TO EXHAUST</data>
      <data key="d1">ENGINEERING_CONTROL</data>
      <data key="d2">Mechanical ventilation setting in which the front and rear bus ventilation fans operated in exhaust mode. This configuration produced substantially higher ACH than supply mode and reduced modeled infection risk when windows were closed.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.93</data>
      <data key="d4">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee_chunk_2</data>
      <data key="d5">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee</data>
    </node>
    <node id="VENTILATION FANS SET TO SUPPLY">
      <data key="d0">VENTILATION FANS SET TO SUPPLY</data>
      <data key="d1">ENGINEERING_CONTROL</data>
      <data key="d2">Mechanical ventilation setting in which the front and rear bus ventilation fans operated in supply mode. In the study it served as the comparison condition for exhaust mode and resulted in lower ACH.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.74</data>
      <data key="d4">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee_chunk_2</data>
      <data key="d5">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee</data>
    </node>
    <node id="AIR CONDITIONING (AC) ON">
      <data key="d0">AIR CONDITIONING (AC) ON</data>
      <data key="d1">ENGINEERING_CONTROL</data>
      <data key="d2">Operational state of the bus air-conditioning system during which particle spread was slower than CO2 spread. The text suggests this occurred because particles may have been trapped by the AC prefilter, indicating a filtration-related transport effect.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.82</data>
      <data key="d4">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee_chunk_2</data>
      <data key="d5">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee</data>
    </node>
    <node id="AC UNIT WITH AN APPROPRIATE FILTER">
      <data key="d0">AC UNIT WITH AN APPROPRIATE FILTER</data>
      <data key="d1">ENGINEERING_CONTROL</data>
      <data key="d2">Recommended filtration intervention in which the bus AC unit is equipped with a more suitable filter to trap airborne particles. The authors state that infection risk can be reduced by this measure.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee_chunk_2</data>
      <data key="d5">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee</data>
    </node>
    <node id="PREFILTER ON THE AC UNIT">
      <data key="d0">PREFILTER ON THE AC UNIT</data>
      <data key="d1">ENGINEERING_CONTROL</data>
      <data key="d2">Existing filter component on the bus AC unit that may trap particles. It is presented as the likely reason particle spread was about half that of CO2 when the AC was on.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.79</data>
      <data key="d4">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee_chunk_2</data>
      <data key="d5">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee</data>
    </node>
    <node id="PARTICLE SPREAD RATE ABOUT HALF OF CO2 WITH AC ON">
      <data key="d0">PARTICLE SPREAD RATE ABOUT HALF OF CO2 WITH AC ON</data>
      <data key="d1">DOSE_OR_RATE</data>
      <data key="d2">Comparative transport result showing that with the AC on, the spread rate of particles was about half that of CO2. This finding supports a filtration effect from the AC system.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.84</data>
      <data key="d4">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee_chunk_2</data>
      <data key="d5">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee</data>
    </node>
    <node id="MORE THAN DOUBLE ACH VERSUS SUPPLY MODE">
      <data key="d0">MORE THAN DOUBLE ACH VERSUS SUPPLY MODE</data>
      <data key="d1">DOSE_OR_RATE</data>
      <data key="d2">Comparative ventilation result indicating that ACH with both front and rear fans set to exhaust was more than double the ACH when both were set to supply.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.72</data>
      <data key="d4">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee_chunk_2</data>
      <data key="d5">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee</data>
    </node>
    <node id="SARS-COV-2">
      <data key="d0">SARS-COV-2</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Airborne viral pathogen of concern in the study. The bus ventilation and filtration interventions were evaluated in the context of reducing COVID-19 transmission risk.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.99</data>
      <data key="d4">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee_chunk_2,e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee_chunk_6,e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee_chunk_9</data>
      <data key="d5">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee</data>
    </node>
    <node id="92% REDUCTION IN AVERAGE INFECTION RISK">
      <data key="d0">92% REDUCTION IN AVERAGE INFECTION RISK</data>
      <data key="d1">EFFECTIVENESS_MEASURE</data>
      <data key="d2">Modeled result showing that average infection risk was reduced by 92% in the moving bus with windows open compared with windows closed. | Modeled result showing that exhaust fan operation reduced average infection risk by 35% when the bus was moving with windows closed.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.99</data>
      <data key="d4">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee_chunk_2</data>
      <data key="d5">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee</data>
      <data key="d6">35% REDUCTION IN AVERAGE INFECTION RISK</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ROUTE BUS">
      <data key="d0">ROUTE BUS</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">Transport setting in which ventilation, air conditioning, particle transport, and infection risk were evaluated. Although not a hospital area, it is the relevant physical environment available within the allowed type system.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.88</data>
      <data key="d4">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee_chunk_2</data>
      <data key="d5">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee</data>
    </node>
    <node id="MODIFIED WELLS-RILEY EQUATION CALCULATIONS">
      <data key="d0">MODIFIED WELLS-RILEY EQUATION CALCULATIONS</data>
      <data key="d1">VALIDATION_STUDY</data>
      <data key="d2">Modeling approach used to estimate average infection risk under different bus ventilation conditions. These calculations produced the reported 92% and 35% risk-reduction estimates.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.94</data>
      <data key="d4">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee_chunk_2</data>
      <data key="d5">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee</data>
    </node>
    <node id="BUS VENTILATION CONFIGURATION">
      <data key="d0">BUS VENTILATION CONFIGURATION</data>
      <data key="d1">ENGINEERING_CONTROL</data>
      <data key="d2">Ventilation conditions in the commuter bus, including windows closed, five windows fully open, door opening during stop-and-go operation, and bus movement at different speeds.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.96</data>
      <data key="d4">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee_chunk_3</data>
      <data key="d5">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CO2 EMISSION AND MONITORING SYSTEM">
      <data key="d0">CO2 EMISSION AND MONITORING SYSTEM</data>
      <data key="d1">VALIDATION_STUDY</data>
      <data key="d2">Experimental tracer-gas setup using CO2 emission and monitoring points in the bus to determine ventilation performance.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.78</data>
      <data key="d4">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee_chunk_3</data>
      <data key="d5">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee</data>
    </node>
    <node id="PARTICLE EMISSION SYSTEM">
      <data key="d0">PARTICLE EMISSION SYSTEM</data>
      <data key="d1">VALIDATION_STUDY</data>
      <data key="d2">Experimental particle release setup used to characterize airflow and ventilation-related behavior in the bus.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee_chunk_3</data>
      <data key="d5">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee</data>
    </node>
    <node id="COMMUTER BUS CABIN">
      <data key="d0">COMMUTER BUS CABIN</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">Interior passenger space of the commuter bus where ventilation, CO2, and particle measurements were conducted.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.74</data>
      <data key="d4">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee_chunk_3</data>
      <data key="d5">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee</data>
    </node>
    <node id="OPEN WINDOWS">
      <data key="d0">OPEN WINDOWS</data>
      <data key="d1">ENGINEERING_CONTROL</data>
      <data key="d2">Natural ventilation intervention in the bus created by opening windows. The figures compare different numbers and configurations of open windows, such as right front with left rear, right front with right rear, and right rear with left rear, to assess their effect on ventilation performance.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.96</data>
      <data key="d4">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee_chunk_4</data>
      <data key="d5">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee</data>
    </node>
    <node id="VENTILATION FAN OPERATION">
      <data key="d0">VENTILATION FAN OPERATION</data>
      <data key="d1">ENGINEERING_CONTROL</data>
      <data key="d2">Mechanical ventilation intervention involving operation of the bus ventilation fans. Figure 5 evaluates the effect of front and rear fan operation on air changes per hour in the bus without mannequins.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.93</data>
      <data key="d4">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee_chunk_4</data>
      <data key="d5">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee</data>
    </node>
    <node id="ACH">
      <data key="d0">ACH</data>
      <data key="d1">DOSE_OR_RATE</data>
      <data key="d2">Air changes per hour, the main ventilation-rate metric used to quantify how window opening and ventilation fan operation affect air exchange in the bus.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.98</data>
      <data key="d4">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee_chunk_4</data>
      <data key="d5">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee</data>
    </node>
    <node id="CO2">
      <data key="d0">CO2</data>
      <data key="d1">AIRBORNE_PATHOGEN</data>
      <data key="d2">Carbon dioxide used as an airborne tracer of exhaled breath transport in the bus experiments. Although not a pathogen biologically, it is the closest schema-compatible airborne target discussed in relation to inhalation exposure and ventilation performance.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.74</data>
      <data key="d4">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee_chunk_4</data>
      <data key="d5">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee</data>
    </node>
    <node id="INHALATION VOLUME OF CO2">
      <data key="d0">INHALATION VOLUME OF CO2</data>
      <data key="d1">EFFECTIVENESS_MEASURE</data>
      <data key="d2">Exposure-related outcome defined as inhalation volume of CO2 relative to the emitted volume. In Figure 6, this measure is reported for stationary tests with mannequins for emissions from the right rearmost part of the bus and from the front center standing position.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.91</data>
      <data key="d4">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee_chunk_4</data>
      <data key="d5">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee</data>
    </node>
    <node id="BUS">
      <data key="d0">BUS</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">The enclosed vehicle cabin in which ventilation and exposure experiments were conducted. Within the available schema, it serves as the physical zone to which the engineering controls are applied and where ACH and CO2 inhalation outcomes are measured.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee_chunk_4</data>
      <data key="d5">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee</data>
    </node>
    <node id="STATIONARY TESTS">
      <data key="d0">STATIONARY TESTS</data>
      <data key="d1">VALIDATION_STUDY</data>
      <data key="d2">Experimental tests conducted with the bus stationary in the car barn at the Fujisawa plant. These tests were used to evaluate ACH and, with mannequins, inhalation volume of CO2.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.89</data>
      <data key="d4">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee_chunk_4</data>
      <data key="d5">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee</data>
    </node>
    <node id="MOVING TESTS">
      <data key="d0">MOVING TESTS</data>
      <data key="d1">VALIDATION_STUDY</data>
      <data key="d2">Experimental tests conducted with the bus moving outdoors at Tsukuba. These tests were used to evaluate ACH under dynamic operating conditions.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.83</data>
      <data key="d4">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee_chunk_4</data>
      <data key="d5">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee</data>
    </node>
    <node id="MANNEQUINS">
      <data key="d0">MANNEQUINS</data>
      <data key="d1">VALIDATION_STUDY</data>
      <data key="d2">Experimental mannequin setup used in the stationary exposure tests to assess inhalation volume of CO2 relative to emitted volume from specified source positions in the bus.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.67</data>
      <data key="d4">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee_chunk_4</data>
      <data key="d5">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee</data>
    </node>
    <node id="AC">
      <data key="d0">AC</data>
      <data key="d1">ENGINEERING_CONTROL</data>
      <data key="d2">Air-conditioning operation in the bus, explicitly compared as on versus off in the measurement conditions. In this context it is a ventilation-related engineering control that changes airflow and likely affects transport of exhaled CO2 and particles.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee_chunk_5</data>
      <data key="d5">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee</data>
    </node>
    <node id="WINDOWS OPEN">
      <data key="d0">WINDOWS OPEN</data>
      <data key="d1">ENGINEERING_CONTROL</data>
      <data key="d2">A natural-ventilation condition in which bus windows are open. This operational control changes air exchange with the outdoors and is one of the explicit exposure conditions in the stationary city bus experiments.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.88</data>
      <data key="d4">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee_chunk_5</data>
      <data key="d5">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee</data>
    </node>
    <node id="FAN SUPPLY (FRONT) &amp; EXHAUST (REAR)">
      <data key="d0">FAN SUPPLY (FRONT) &amp; EXHAUST (REAR)</data>
      <data key="d1">ENGINEERING_CONTROL</data>
      <data key="d2">A mechanical ventilation configuration using front supply and rear exhaust fans. It is an explicit airflow-control condition tested in the stationary city bus exposure experiments.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee_chunk_5</data>
      <data key="d5">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee</data>
    </node>
    <node id="FAN SUPPLY (FRONT) &amp; SUPPLY (REAR)">
      <data key="d0">FAN SUPPLY (FRONT) &amp; SUPPLY (REAR)</data>
      <data key="d1">ENGINEERING_CONTROL</data>
      <data key="d2">A mechanical airflow configuration using supply fans at both the front and rear of the bus. It is listed as a distinct tested ventilation condition in the normalized exposure figure.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.86</data>
      <data key="d4">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee_chunk_5</data>
      <data key="d5">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee</data>
    </node>
    <node id="P CO2">
      <data key="d0">P CO2</data>
      <data key="d1">DOSE_OR_RATE</data>
      <data key="d2">Position-specific or inhalation-related CO2 metric shown in the figures, including inhalation volume of CO2 relative to emitted volume and its relationship to particle measurements. It functions as a quantitative exposure proxy in the bus experiments.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.91</data>
      <data key="d4">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee_chunk_5</data>
      <data key="d5">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee</data>
    </node>
    <node id="P PARTICLES">
      <data key="d0">P PARTICLES</data>
      <data key="d1">DOSE_OR_RATE</data>
      <data key="d2">Position-specific particle measurement used in Figure 8 to compare with P CO2 across bus measurement locations. It represents a quantitative airborne exposure metric in the study.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.87</data>
      <data key="d4">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee_chunk_5</data>
      <data key="d5">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee</data>
    </node>
    <node id="NORMALIZED EXPOSURE DATA">
      <data key="d0">NORMALIZED EXPOSURE DATA</data>
      <data key="d1">EFFECTIVENESS_MEASURE</data>
      <data key="d2">The comparative exposure outcome reported for different stationary city bus ventilation conditions. It is the main effectiveness measure shown in Figure 9 for evaluating how ventilation configurations alter exposure.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee_chunk_5</data>
      <data key="d5">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee</data>
    </node>
    <node id="RELATIONSHIP BETWEEN P CO2 AND P PARTICLES">
      <data key="d0">RELATIONSHIP BETWEEN P CO2 AND P PARTICLES</data>
      <data key="d1">EFFECTIVENESS_MEASURE</data>
      <data key="d2">The observed association between the CO2-based exposure proxy and particle measurements in the bus across five positions, compared with AC on and off. This serves as an effectiveness measure for assessing whether CO2 tracks particle exposure under different ventilation states.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.82</data>
      <data key="d4">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee_chunk_5</data>
      <data key="d5">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee</data>
    </node>
    <node id="STATIONARY CITY BUS">
      <data key="d0">STATIONARY CITY BUS</data>
      <data key="d1">VALIDATION_STUDY</data>
      <data key="d2">The stationary bus experimental setting used to compare normalized exposure under multiple ventilation conditions, including windows open and different fan configurations.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.84</data>
      <data key="d4">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee_chunk_5</data>
      <data key="d5">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee</data>
    </node>
    <node id="MOVING TESTS WITH MANNEQUINS">
      <data key="d0">MOVING TESTS WITH MANNEQUINS</data>
      <data key="d1">VALIDATION_STUDY</data>
      <data key="d2">The moving-bus mannequin experiment in which inhalation volume of CO2 relative to emitted volume was measured at indicated positions. It provides experimental validation data on exposure patterns under transport conditions.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee_chunk_5</data>
      <data key="d5">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee</data>
    </node>
    <node id="FIVE MEASUREMENT POSITIONS">
      <data key="d0">FIVE MEASUREMENT POSITIONS</data>
      <data key="d1">VALIDATION_STUDY</data>
      <data key="d2">The five spatial sampling locations in the bus used to evaluate the relationship between P CO2 and P particles with AC on and off.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.68</data>
      <data key="d4">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee_chunk_5</data>
      <data key="d5">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee</data>
    </node>
    <node id="NATURAL VENTILATION STRATEGY">
      <data key="d0">NATURAL VENTILATION STRATEGY</data>
      <data key="d1">ENGINEERING_CONTROL</data>
      <data key="d2">A ventilation-based engineering control that uses outdoor air exchange to reduce indoor airborne transmission risk. In the text, it is specifically discussed as a strategy to prevent COVID-19 airborne transmission in a school building.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.96</data>
      <data key="d4">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee_chunk_6</data>
      <data key="d5">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee</data>
    </node>
    <node id="VENTILATION CONCEPTS">
      <data key="d0">VENTILATION CONCEPTS</data>
      <data key="d1">ENGINEERING_CONTROL</data>
      <data key="d2">A general class of indoor-air engineering controls based on airflow management and ventilation to prevent aerosol transmission of infectious viruses. In the text, these concepts are discussed for schools and specifically in relation to SARS-CoV-2.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.85</data>
      <data key="d4">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee_chunk_6</data>
      <data key="d5">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee</data>
    </node>
    <node id="DIFFERENT VENTILATION STRATEGIES">
      <data key="d0">DIFFERENT VENTILATION STRATEGIES</data>
      <data key="d1">ENGINEERING_CONTROL</data>
      <data key="d2">A comparative set of ventilation control approaches evaluated for their effect on indoor contaminant accumulation and droplet dispersion. In the text, they are studied in a hospital lift environment.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee_chunk_6,e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee_chunk_7</data>
      <data key="d5">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee</data>
    </node>
    <node id="AIR CHANGE RATES">
      <data key="d0">AIR CHANGE RATES</data>
      <data key="d1">DOSE_OR_RATE</data>
